happiest of yule tides, everyone! 
first holiday without nana helen, and it felt a little empty not calling her to hear how much i didn't need to send her something that could only possibly cost a fraction of what she spent on me. does anyone else's parent gift them something really nice and then act like even just a card is far too much?! i still think the best gift nana helen ever gave me was her first year being an, 'empty nester.' she made care baskets for all us grandkids that had cleaning essentials, emergenC for the cold weather, and the comfiest pajamas!
well, i outgrew the pajamas, and i took all the emergenC, but i still use the laundry basket and while the extendable fan blade cleaner is getting a vacation, it has been through many new fluffs! to think she got embarrassed thinking we would be insulted, and it's my absolute favorite because it was so useful and thoughtful. 
however, i might have accidentally let my sister know about my nephews secret gnome village...sorry sis! 
wherever you are, whatever you celebrate, no matter what is going on in your life; be present. the best thing you can do is be present. if you can tell your loved ones about your day later, you'll want to know what happened. if you're missing loved ones this season, live as fully as you possibly can for them. 𝐶𝑜𝑚𝑓𝑜𝑟𝑡 : a saga

theo had his annual boosters, was told he has a strong heart, great lungs, and one of the sweetest/calmest/funniest personalities. (but we all knew that!) he did get some signs of aging; teeth potentially needing professional care in the near future despite daily brushing, a luxating patella in one knee, and the mystery of his body destroying platelets faster than it can create them. after some testing, an x-ray, and lots of discussion, we're all stumped. his alopecia is getting better, and his seizures have settled down, but both his vet and i think they may be tied to whatever is going on his his blood production. we're adding in some vitamin K to his diet along with melatonin, which apparently also helps with hair growth, and we'll keep an eye out to see if any other symptoms occur. thankfully he has a good skin flush, no fading in his gums, he doesn't have any urinary problems nor blank staring at the walls, and no issues clotting, so his veterinarian didn't think screening for cancer was necessary. she gave him an A+ and some recommendations for boosting his blood production levels, and possible causes of temporary anemia, and of course NOW he's jumping off things like evel knievel. 

just wanted to give the internet family an update, and say how appreciated it is to have so many we've met, in person or not, care about my little man. he truly is a very special pup, and i am so grateful to say he's my best friend. thank you all for loving us and welcoming us into your lives!

something that has been on my mind for a while, like years, is the phrase, "its ok to not be ok." to be honest, i hate it. if you've ever been going through it, you know the feeling of not being ok is anything but...ok. 

while i'm aware the phrase has good intentions, i think it's misleading and a bit discouraging. because, in my experience at least, i've seen people put off getting necessary help because, "the way i feel is ok." (therefore does not require attention.) or, in a personal experience, when trying to ask for help being dismissed with the phrase. thanks barbara, but should i see a therapist/psychiatrist about it?

not that any non-professional should be giving advice, but if someone comes to you, rather than just saying you're not qualified/comfortable with the conversation, a simple, "i actually don't know, have you checked with resources through your insurance/anonymous online?" gives a direction, shows you care, but that you're not the one.

people don't know where to go, and a lot of the influencers getting paid by places are advertising help that; is out of pocket, over booked and understaffed, or on an unlicensed level. 

trust me, i know having a, "i went to school for this," answer can be annoying over the, "i've been through something similar," one, but be patient with your provider and yourself. it may take a couple tries, a couple different people, before you find that safe space to work on making the 'not ok,' 'ok,' again. 

instead of, "its ok to not be ok," just know, "it's ok to have a journey," whether that be mental battles, seeking help, or overcoming ED/SH. your feelings are real, they may not have logic, but emotions don't function that way unfortunately. it's ok to have a journey.
stay positive,
💋Xoxo

depression is a weird monster. it lurks in corners, it watches and waits, and it will never let you know it's next move. 

after some medical stuff, an allergy cold, and poor theo getting an ear infection...it feels like we've been some form of sick in the dohalick household for ages. the body responds accordingly in order to heal, and it's left everyone feeling a little 'meh.' needing rest, being weak, constantly tired, all of us have cycled through it at one point since the new year. as it's been my turn, i've tried out little things to not feel defeated, but the best has been the support from my boys. (i contemplated doing a video just getting out of bed with theo cheering me on, but who gets out of bed to stage a scene and set up a camera? some of you guys are dedicated to the craft!) i mentioned feeling silly doing GRWM videos, and jared didn't say anything in particular, just asked me, "does it make you feel good?" and yeah, it has. it feels more productive to spend fifteen minutes making a video than to load around. it really is the little things. 

if you're in the winter to spring slump, you're not alone. allergies are more than itchy eyes and runny noses, and when it makes you feel icky, you may just FEEL down. your physical body effects your psychological body more than just mental health walks boosting your mood, and it's important to acknowledge that. if you're feeling blue in this transition of seasons, ask yourself what's happening around you; weather, health, sleep quality, etc. it may be an easy fix, it may be an ongoing journey, it may just be a wait till the sun comes out. either way, you're going to get through it!

stay positive,

part of sustainability is quality. clothing makes up 30-40% of waste every year, with textile factories using 79 TRILLION liters of water. inflation sucks, and things are only getting more expensive, i get it. but fast fashion comes at a cost, other than on your wallet. 

brands like Shein, Forever 21, and Fashionova may be more affordable in the moment; but the fabrics used aren't meant to last and are majority chemical process so that they do in fact break down over time creating a repeat consumer. 

it's considered a luxury now to afford brands that will last through the years, admittedly i've purchased both cheaper options as well as some quality pieces, and it's hard when you have an immediate need and are low on funds. it doesn't have to be 100% made by your great grandmother, but taking steps to reduce your consumption help. maybe it's rewearing a dress purchased for a specific event, checking that your makeup pads contain cotton from the USA, or just practicing cooking at home more frequently. every little bit helps.

social media is such an interesting thing, it's a place where you can choose how you would like to be perceived. people can take beautiful photos and video to paint themselves in an extravagant light, people can write stories to make themselves a hero in a completely fabricated situation, and often times we find ourselves believing that someone who is completely infatuated with themselves is simply raw and wholesome. 
i hope you get the impression i have a kind heart, that i am passionate about the world, and that i have good intentions though sometimes poor execution. i hope you get that vibe from me.
what i am is easily excitable, quickly exhausted socially, and a logical processor when it comes to emotions. i enjoy more witty humor than slap stick comedy, i am extremely planned, and i often feel lonely when i am surrounded by many. i don't have a 24/7 twin type relationship with a best friend who call each other derogatory names in a loving way, but a network of beautiful women (all coincidentally sharing the name hannah, and joanna) who i don't speak with often, but it is always like we pick up right where we left off. i do in fact love adventures, though most days now are spent cozy at home, and despite commonalities of where i live i rarely drink and do not smoke nor indulge in edibles. 
i might not be much on paper, nor as exciting as i used to be or as others, but i am happy. and that's been the goal since the beginning, and i just hope that wherever you are in your life you find that too...and start creating an image of yourself that your internal news feed would thrive on.
stay positive,

i keep seeing the phrase, "agree to disagree," online lately. to be perfectly honest, i think this is a very dismissive way to address a difference of opinion. particularly that i keep seeing it for matters that come from a good place, matters that deserve to be heard and at the very least considered.

instead of thinking you have your opinions and someone else has their own, try changing your mindset. "i don't fully understand where you are coming from in this matter, but next time i will take your thinking into consideration for my decision making." we live in a selfish world where "let bygones be bygones" is normal and accepted, and that's a lazy way of thinking.

personally, i've seen this phrase with; political discussion of rights, matters of safety that involve the unsuspecting public, and even in some topics of racial discrimination. if you're seeing this and consider yourself a friend, please opt to do better at being considerate of others. i'm not the type of friend to watch you stagnant in growth, i want you to be your best self, so challenge yourself to be more open to others ideas/thoughts/opinions.

you're not always going to agree with someone else, but you don't have to push their concerns aside. if you find yourself disagreeing with someone, instead of dismissing them, maybe ask them where their reasoning lies; maybe weigh your personal feelings vs theirs; maybe look for a compromise that encompasses the perspectives outside your own.

what is happiness if you only keep it to yourself? 

i think it's important to remember that, "the internet isn't real," but i also find it very valuable to not filter your content consumption with other's low moments. because what you put in your mind is truly what you will put out. 
it's easy to become jealous of other's success when you feel that the world has been unjust to you, but reveling in others struggles won't put you any further ahead. misery loves its company, to the point of becoming joe goldberg from, 'you.' (obsessing to the point of murdering love, and yes that was an intentional play on words. RIP, girlfriend.) if you hang out with only your self pity, envy, and malice you will eventually kill the little light inside of you that so desperately wants to shine. we create a fire by fanning the sparks, but fan too much and you'll put it out. 
so, next time you find yourself down to your last embers, start using those gusts of negative energy to push you. it's not easy, but if you're willing to think creatively and look for solutions to the problems, a bad situation can actually become the inspiration you need to find your own success. just as a fire can reignite, you can too. 
Xx.

so, here are a few thoughts @allhailmedicalsales provoked for me from episode 77 of the state of medtech;

1. confidence doesn't mean feeling ready to do something, it means you have simple faith in the results. it means you present things for what they are, honest whether you have solutions or bandaids, what you are capable of and willing to put in.
2. whether you are selling a product, yourself to a new friend group, or an idea, you better believe in yourself. no one continues to purchase/socialize/revisit lies.
3. literally everything is in your head. your truth, your experience, is completely different from the person next to you. even in the same situation, so start basing yourself in objective truths; aka facts. 

the sun will always be a burning ball of flame, the earth will continue to turn, and your mind will always control your perception of reality. stop waiting for things to happen, procrastination is not a friend of manifestation. wake up and choose to be the person you want yourself to be each day, because when you start acting upon that person, they will become your reality instead of your dream. 

and if you're not confident, that's ok, just grow a little everyday.

with october around the corner, i'd also like to emphasize breast cancer awareness; and say men and women alike can have breast cancer, so all of you should be feeling your tata's! as well as asking your physician at your next check up about getting tested for BRCA 1&2. (an inherited gene mutation that increases your chances) anything that reduces your risk and prolongs a life of health and happiness, right? it may be weird at first, but there are so many resources on ways to get to know your body and practice regular self examination. please do your research, and please don't put off your health. you deserve to be in the know when it comes to your health and wellness.

this isn't a well thought out mental health post, this is physical health post.

getting into the cooler season, there's a lot of solo hikers, solo boarders/skiers, and so on and so forth. PLEASE for goodness sakes;

1. tell someone where you are going,  and your expected timeframe.
2. pack a first aid kit
3. pack said kit in the easiest accessible place

these seem obvious and simple, yet they are the most commonly forgotten practices. i've had to go collect a couple friends from broken legs, one a broken arm, and given a few some impromptu butterfly "stitches" to be able to get them to proper care. accidents happen! and trust me, the "it wont happen to me, i'm careful" mentality is the worst thing you can adopt.

things you should always carry;

1. some type of communication. cell phone to emergency flare, whatever area you are going to make sure you'll have a way to contact someone.
2. squeezie nozzle bottle or just a plastic bottle. if you get a cut or hash outdoors, a squeeze bottle or being able to poke a hole in a plastic bottle can serve as a temporary pressure washer.
3. gauze and tape. even if you don't carry individual bandages or butterfly clips, being able to close and cover a wound is important. 
4. emergency OTC meds. i'll be harsh on this, idngaff if you're an anti pill person. at the least carry something bayer or something, because if you run into someone having a high class heart attack you are not going to be able to just escort them down the mountain. have something to help ease their pain or at the very least keep them or you alive until you can seek help.
5. whistle. like a R-word whistle. something extremely loud. even if you're the only human in the woods, you are not the only living thing. you could use it to frighten off an attack, to signal to other parties you are there and need help, just carry one.

these things don't have to be huge, or in bulk, so if you're trying to pack light you still can. but please, be safe out there.

we love to cook in our home, but both of us work. i'm blessed to work from home, but that doesn't really give me free time because my days are still 'at' work. so we prep a few days in advance, and we use the crockpot a ton this time of year. i'm blessed to have met jared, because i used to have a strict diet of eggs and sausage for breakfast, spinach and hardboiled eggs with mushrooms for lunch 1, a stuffed lox bagel for lunch 2, and grilled chicken with broccoli and rice for dinner EVERY SINGLE DAY. i didn't really mind, probably because i didn't know better, but how boring was i? 

now, i live off a phrase i heard my grandma say once, "i feel like i need a vegetable." i know meat will be taken care with jared and his butcher box around, so i try to make a variety of veggies and i only measure my proteins to make sure i'm getting enough. the scale does not interfere with anything else on my plate at this time, but once we get closer to summer i might lean a little more towards catering aesthetics. i like to eat with the thirds method, one third of my plate for my meat, another for veggies, and then some grains or starches. i've just found that eating this way helps me feel satisfied, reduces gas/bloat, and  makes me feel energized instead of sluggishly digesting. but i also have a pretty high activity level. 

training is a whole other conversation i'll make a video for, but my basic split is: whatever jared says. he used to be a personal trainer, he is certified, and still works in the medical field. i don't do a lot of the planning, i'm more our recovery person. what that's been looking like is (out of space, in the comments!)

alexa, play "let it snow," by dean martin.

we don't have alexa, but if we did, that's the best version and i will not be swayed.

something i am trying to practice are things i used to do when i was working three jobs and struggling to balance life;

if you don't have five minutes, take ten. 

meditation should be a time to reorganize your thoughts, it shouldn't be rushed. whether you listen to singing bowls, or use your time to get ready for the day, workout, whatever centering looks like for you; give yourself the time you deserve to collect yourself.

it's not perfect, but it's a new year and it's important to acknowledge that it's not all new and shiny for everyone. it's ok if you didn't get a running start at resolutions, you have all year ahead of you.
